(296, 115, 'Port Blair', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Anchored between the Bay of Bengal and the Andaman Sea are a set of sun soaked islands called the Andaman and Nicobar Islands. Port Blair also called the &#39;Veritable Garden of Eden&#39; is the capital of this Indian Territory, and rightly so!<br />\n	Port Blair was affected by the Boxing Day Tsunami in 2004 but has recovered fast; though parts of its famous Corbyn&#39;s Cove Beach were washed away, its green coconut palm fringed beaches and blue seas still beckon invitingly. Ask your Port Blair guide to hold you a seat at the Light and Sound Show at the Cellular Jail, a national monument famous for housing criminal and even famous political prisoners of the British Raj. Extend your insight into the British times by exploring the ghostly ruins reclaimed by fauna at the Ross Island, a boat ride away. The capital city hosts&rsquo; museums, a zoo and marine national park, but the real attraction is experiencing nature at her awe inspiring best be it hiking up Mount Harriet, snorkeling amidst the coral reefs at North Bay or sprawling at the pristine white sand beach of Jolli Buoy!</p>\n', 1, 0, 100, '11.67', '92.76', 'port-blair', 0, 1),
(297, 116, 'Hyderabad', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Claiming the heartlands of south-central India, this sprawling megalopolis is now one of the largest on the entire sub-continent; a veritable mishmash of digitised internet and communications firms, shiny new shopping malls and glistening high-rises. But, under the modern veneer lies a distinct cultural identity, a unique mix of South Indian culture influenced by the Nizam dynasties who held sway on this once princely state.<br />\n	Most Hyderabad tour guides will point first time visitors to the centre of the old city, where it&rsquo;s possible to weave between the streams of rickshaws under the gaze of the iconic Charminar, the looming Mecca Masjid mosque and the sprawling Golconda Fort, where tales of ancient India still lurk between the crevices and cracks. Then there are the exquisite Qutb Shahi Tombs and the endless collections of the Nizam Museum to explore, before one gives in to the lure of a good round of shopping amidst the plentiful pearl shops, yards of pochampalli silk and wax bangles at Laad Bazaar.<br />\n	Hyderabad&rsquo;s gastronomic brilliance is yet another feather in its cap, and guests should perhaps head to one of the city&rsquo;s bubbling food bazaars at Begumpet or Monda, or maybe drop into a regional curry house for a taste of its famous Hyderabadi biryani (that is, if you can handle the spices!).</p>\n', 1, 0, 100, '17.40', '78.48', 'hyderabad', 0, 1),
(298, 116, 'Visakhapatnam', 'Vishakapatnam, Vishakhapatnam', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	More commonly referred to as Vizag, this industrial city in India attracts tourists for its&rsquo; pristine coast, untouched beaches, and picturesque landscape. The shoreline&rsquo;s rocky waters have made swimming unsafe and ill advised, and one usually finds locals strolling on the sand or relaxing on benches in their best clothing. Any good Visakhapatnam tour guide will remind you that the city&rsquo;s beaches are not the only part of its&rsquo; natural scenery worth visiting.<br />\n	The Kambalakonda nature preserve is a greenery-drenched hiking trail overlooking the ocean. Similarly, Kailasagiri&rsquo;s ski lift-styled ropeway delivers visitors to the top of an overlook with restaurants and shops, where breathtaking sights serve as a reminder for Vizag&rsquo;s seaside beauty. &nbsp;Catch a train passing through tunnels to meet with the indigenous tribes at the pleasant hill station of Araku Valley. Stop by at the Borra Caves to marvel at the natural sculptures of million year old stalactites and stalagmites. Scenic appeal apart, no visit to Vizag is complete without visiting the beautiful Simachalam temple nestled among green hills. All this and more; clearly exceeds the tourist&rsquo;s expectations from an industrial city, naval base and port!</p>\n', 1, 0, 100, '17.73', '83.30', 'visakhapatnam', 0, 1),
(299, 116, 'Vijayawada', '', '', 1, 0, 100, '16.52', '80.63', 'vijayawada', 0, 1),
(300, 116, 'Warangal', 'Varangal', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Four stone gateways, a great fortress and a collection of impressive temples, this former Kakatiya capital is one of India&#39;s World Heritage sites. Whether it&#39;s to view the sunset of the two lakes on the outskirts of the town or to stroll along the stone monuments constructed centuries ago, a day in Warangal will leave you breathless at the architectural mastery on show.<br />\n	The city maybe overshadowed by it&#39;s big neighbour Hyderabad but the locals will no doubt regale you with stories of their fabulous temples. Remnants of the impressive stone fortress shadow over the city along with The Thousand Pillar temple which lives by it&#39;s name with intricate pillars on a structure which is exactly 1m above the ground. Both of these are must visits in every Warangal tourist guide. A delightful way to end the day in this jewel of Andhra Pradesh would be sitting by the Bhadrakali temple and watching the sun set over it&#39;s adjoining lake. This is a spiritual relaxing destination for any travellers wanting to revel in southern India&#39;s architectural splendour.</p>\n', 1, 0, 100, '18.01', '79.58', 'warangal', 0, 1),
