(429, 157, 'Flagstaff', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	As the self-proclaimed recreational center of Northern Arizona, a trip to Flagstaff is often bursting with activity and deftly void of boredom. Located at the base of Arizona&rsquo;s highest mountain, Humphrey&rsquo;s Peak, the stage is immediately set for a city rich in outdoor adventure. With a height of 12,634, Flagstaff&rsquo;s highland is the perfect setting for any hiking and biking extraordinaire, but cross-country and downhill skiers embark for the city when snow covers its&rsquo; mountainous range. Local reservoirs and lakes converts dedicated land-lovers to its&rsquo; realms, as its&rsquo; aquatic draw pulls locals and visitors alike to boats, kayaks, and fishing reels in the Arizona sun.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	As any Flagstaff tour guide will tell you, the city&rsquo;s wonder continues beyond its&rsquo; borders. Just 80 miles from the Grand Canyon, a stay in Flagstaff offers a day trip to one of the country&rsquo;s greatest natural scenes. Still, nearby canyons engulf the scenery, providing those uninterested in a long road trip with shorter, mini outings to relish in the city&rsquo;s innate grandeur.<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n', 1, 0, 220, '35.19', '-111.62', 'flagstaff', 0, 1),
