(829, 256, 'Barranquilla', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Barranquilla is the entertainment hotspot of Colombia, offering enough excitement for the whole country. Of course, Barranquilla offers water adventure activities such as swimming and diving, but the culture of celebration thrives in this city. The rhythm of the cumbia dance is the heartbeat of the city, and you will likely find yourself singing and dancing along before you leave.<br />\n	A Barranquilla tour guide can help you unlock the rhythms of the city by finding the best locations for food, parties, and attractions. Of course, the most notable thing about Barranquilla is its Carnival festival. In fact, Carnival is so famous that UNESCO designated it a &ldquo;Masterpiece of the Oral and Intangible Heritage of Humanity.&rdquo; The entire city is involved in this diverse celebration of dance, music, and culture, working together to form one of the best parades and parties worldwide. In addition to the excitement of Carnival, enjoy the vibrant nightlife and fantastic restaurants of Barranquilla all year round, and be sure to tour the award-winning historic Plaza San Nicolas and El Prado neighborhood. For more activities, check out a soccer game at Estadio Metrapolitano or a show at the Teatro Amira de la Rosa. In Barranquilla, every day is a party, and the many attractions of the city only add to the fun!</p>\n', 1, 0, 46, '10.96', '-74.80', 'barranquilla', 0, 1),
(830, 322, 'Bogota', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Bogot&aacute;, the most populous city in Colombia and one of the tallest capital cities in the world, is located on a high plateau in the Andes region. Called the &ldquo;Athens of South America&rdquo;, be prepared to face a vibrant city, home to pleasant locals and panoramic views, as can be observed from the Monserrate on a clear day.<br />\n	Ask your Bogota tour guide for a historic tour and get swept into the lively neighbourhood of La Candelaria, replete with museums, cathedrals, libraries and very importantly, fantastic dining joints. Colonial houses, cobbled streets and statues of famous South American leaders at the Plaza Bolivar provide a good background for a photo opportunity, as does the Casa de Nari&ntilde;o, the Presidential Palace. Of the mindboggling bevy of museums, the Museo del Oro or the Gold Museum and the Botero Museum are highly recommended. An hour&rsquo;s drive away, the brightly lit Zipaquira Salt Cathedral built inside a salt mine also rate high on a sightseer&rsquo;s list. Shoppers can hit pay dirt at La Zona Rosa, an area that also carries the distinction of being &ldquo;nightlife central&rdquo; for the city. Enjoy the unique flavour of Bogota further by taking a &ldquo;Graffiti Tour&rdquo;, tucking into the local cuisine or just absorbing the greens at the urban city parks that adorn the city.&nbsp;</p>\n', 1, 0, 46, '4.63', '-74.09', 'bogota', 0, 1),
