(1555, 520, 'Cusco', 'Cuzco', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	It&rsquo;s almost impossible to quantify the reasons why so many tourists come to Cusco. Not only is it a UNESCO World Heritage Site in its own right, famed for its encapsulation of the country&rsquo;s 15th and 16th century Incan culture, but it&rsquo;s also one of the best-placed gateways for trekkers looking to make the ubiquitous hike up Machu Picchu in the high peaks of the southern Peruvian Andes. In short it&rsquo;s a city whose tourist guides literally brim with activities to do.<br />\n	Today, the downtown is an attractive melange of post-colonial architecture that bears all the trademarks of Spanish influence, from the wide market square at Plaza de Armas to the buzzing Plaza de San Francisco, the kingpin of Cusco&rsquo;s caf&eacute; culture and chilled-out bar scene. There are also plenty of museums to explore, ranging from regional history exhibitions to some of Peru&rsquo;s finest collections of contemporary art.<br />\n	The city of Cusco is perched high in the mountainous Andean valleys, and represents one of Peru&rsquo;s best enclaves of preserved history. It&rsquo;s a place that&rsquo;s long been considered one of the undisputed &lsquo;must sees&rsquo; for any tourist in the country, whether they intend to make the more ambitious journey further into the Sacred Valley of the Incas or not.</p>\n', 1, 0, 167, '-13.52', '-71.99', 'cusco', 0, 1),
