(1722, 609, 'Port Elizabeth', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Perched out in the cold waters of the South African cape, the &lsquo;windy city&rsquo; of Port Elizabeth forms the buzzing heart of the Nelson Mandela Bay Metro area. Visitors here enjoy a year-round climate of temperate highs and lots of sunshine, making the city&rsquo;s long beach fronts and world-famous surf spots some of the most coveted in all of South Africa, while an array of charter boat companies and yacht clubs have helped establish it as a favourite among travelling sailors looking to explore the famous maritime waters.&nbsp;<br />\n	But, while most of the action here is centred on the seaside, where it&rsquo;s possible to windsurf, scuba dive and simply kickback and relax in the sun, there is still aplenty to do in this Friendly city. Walk the Historic Donkin Heritage trail along the footsteps of the 1820 settlers, drop by for a spot of cricket at St George&#39;s Oval or try your hand at sand boarding at the Maitland Sand Dunes, while the ubiquitous wildlife-spotting opportunities available around town beckon for a visit. For these, head to one of the many game parks that lie just outside of the centre, or enquire at one of the Port Elizabeth tour guide operators, offering excursions to the north of the city.</p>\n', 1, 0, 234, '-33.96', '25.59', 'port-elizabeth', 0, 1),
(1723, 609, 'East London', 'Port Rex, Beacon Bay, Gompo Town, Kwelega, Kwelera, Newlands', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	In many ways the somewhat confusing name of this bustling port town on the Eastern Cape is an apt reminder of its colonial beginnings, and a fine introduction to the wealth of regal Victorian architecture that peppers its now aged central districts. But East London isn&rsquo;t just an urban microcosm of its English big brother; it&rsquo;s got beaches too, and surf. Some of the best in the country in fact.<br />\n	Before heading out to explore the sands and swells around the city though, be sure to ask your East London tour guide about the old City Hall on Oxford Street, with its grandiose Victorian fa&ccedil;ade and painted white and pink hues. And don&rsquo;t leave without seeing the East London Harbour&mdash;the only deep-water river port in the country, and the gateway to the eateries and cafes that line the wharfs along the Buffalo River.<br />\n	Further afield, the most experienced surfers can head to the right-curling point breaks of Nahoon Reef, while beach lovers can seek out the sandy spots at Cove Rock, Glengarriff and picturesque Igoda.</p>\n', 1, 0, 234, '-32.97', '27.87', 'east-london', 0, 1),
