(2205, 729, 'Zagreb', 'Agram, Zágráb', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Running out from the central hub of Ban Jelacic Square, Zagreb&rsquo;s wide streets and cobbled alleyways are peppered with endless examples of Austro-Hungarian imperial grandeur and Balkan bohemianism alike. There&rsquo;s the magnificent twin-spires of the Cathedral of the Assumption of Mary, the sprawling, statue-dotted park of Maksimir, and the palatial frontispieces of King Tomislav Square&mdash;all veritable musts for the budding sightseer heading into town.<br />\n	A jaunt to the bubbling student bars along Tkalciceva Street will show, this is a city with an edgy and divergent side too, which means that anyone interested in pursuing the historical and artistic tendrils of the city a little deeper, should be sure to ask their Zagreb tourist guide for the low down on the quintessential exhibitions of the Muzej Mimara, alongside more quirky spots like the Museum of Broken Relationships or the Dolac farmer&rsquo;s market.<br />\n	Then there&rsquo;s also the looming shadow of Mount Medvednica; a permanent reminder of Zagreb&rsquo;s wonderful natural surroundings. These make for endless hiking trails, refreshing lake swims and even wintertime skiing opportunities, not to mention easy access to some of the country&rsquo;s amazing Adriatic beaches just to the south-west.</p>\n', 1, 0, 93, '45.80', '15.97', 'zagreb', 0, 1),
(2206, 730, 'Granada', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	The beautiful patchwork of Moorish architecture and authentic Andalusian charm that dominates it makes Granada, a true relic of the colonial New World one of the real historical gems of South America. The city&rsquo;s proud epithet &ndash; &lsquo;<em>La Gran Sultana</em>&rsquo; &ndash; honours its colonial mother-town on the Med, while the character of continental Europe is evident in every nook and cranny of it&rsquo;s downtown.<br />\n	Officially the oldest Spanish city in Latin America, Granada&rsquo;s founding took place in 1524, when exploring conquistadores designated it as one of the major trading hubs on Lake Nicaragua. Ask your Granada tour guide for a synopsis of this ancient city&rsquo;s history, and you will be told how Granada has seen its fair share of turmoil from repeated pirate raids throughout the 17<sup>th</sup> century, to feeling the brunt of Nicaragua&rsquo;s civil war in the middle of the 19<sup>th</sup>.<br />\n	But, from the magnificent Moorish churches of Granada&rsquo;s centre, to the enticing beaches and volcano-supported islands on the scenic lake, this city is famed for its healthy vigoron (a dish made from fried cabbage and roast pork), great cigars and lively local character; a veritable &lsquo;must see&rsquo; for every would-be visitor.&nbsp;</p>\n', 1, 0, 158, '11.94', '-85.96', 'granada', 0, 1),
