(2615, 868, 'Ibarra', '', '<p class="fr-tag" style="text-align: justify;">Clutching steadfastly to the low slopes of the Imbabura Volcano, Ibarra is one part peaceful provincial capital and one part frenetic trader town that’s on the up. Consequently, it’s a place where travellers can witness the interfacing of the old and new Ecuador; where the aged faces of whitewashed Spanish cottages straight out of Andalusia rub shoulders with all new tarmacked roadways pumping with machinery and automobiles. </p><p class="fr-tag" style="text-align: justify;">However, it’s definitely the traditional side of things that is winning through here still. The marketplaces still hum with the chatter of Andean Indians, tanned locals still swill aromatic coffees a the Peñaherrera, and every September the town erupts with the Fiesta de los Lagos in a medley of dances and highland rituals. </p><p class="fr-tag" style="text-align: justify;">First-time visitors here should be sure not to miss out on a visit to the bustling Saturday morning market, when the town bulges with handcrafted wools, cotton fabrics and sugar-cane tipples to boot. Nearby, Laguna Yahuarcocha promises a picnic filled day of bird watching and seafood joints, while Ibarra tour guides also recommend delving into pre-Columbian history at the town’s Museo del Banco Central, or breaking out to nearby Otavalo, a volcano-shrouded trading post that found its zenith with the Incas.</p>', 1, 0, 60, '0.36', '-78.13', 'ibarra', 0, 1),
(2616, 869, 'Kutaisi', 'Kutais', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Deciduous Forests and agricultural lands make up the landscape of the legislative capital of Georgia, Kutaisi. The city boasts two world Heritage Sites of UNESCO; the yellowed stone 11th century Bagati Cathedral with its aquamarine roof stands proud on the hilltop and the Medieval Gelati Monastery, its faded paintings adorning it&rsquo;s walls and ceilings bear testimony to its illustrious past as the intellectual centre of Georgia&nbsp; . Let your Kutaisi Travel Guide help you explore the Sataplia Caves alight with coloured lights highlighting the incredible structures of the caves or the footprints of dinosaurs. The Rioni River runs through the city where the Kutaisi State Historical Museum has more than 16&nbsp;000 exhibits depicting centuries of life in Georgia. Culture and art make up the fabric of Georgian society and this can be seen at the David Kakabadze Fine Art Gallery, where over 2800 artworks are displayed featuring the best of 19th and 20th Century Georgian artists. If you happen to be in Kutaisi on the 2nd May join in the festivities of Kutaisoba in the Central Park. Wearing different kinds of masks and traditional Georgian clothing, one is entertained with traditional dancing and folk music.</p>\n', 1, 0, 76, '42.26', '42.72', 'kutaisi', 0, 1),
