(2959, 1018, 'Corfu', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	The picturesque Ionian island of Corfu has seen a history of colonisation by various nations, bequeathing it a unique multi cultural heritage more western than Greek.&nbsp; Also called Kerkyra in Greek, Corfu&rsquo;s old town exudes such magnificence in the fa&ccedil;ade and grandeur of its Classical, Renaissance and Baroque based artistry that the site has been given UNESCO World Heritage status. Facing it, the enormous Spianade Square often offers entertainment all year round, from sports events to the unique oriental collection of artefacts at the Museum of Asian Art positioned at its one end. Corfu town impresses with its museums, churches, palaces and forts, these man made attractions further enhanced by the natural charm of its beaches, rock formations and splendid scenery. A veritable must do for the physically fit is the long distance Corfu Trail; consult your Corfu tour guide map to chart out its route as it meanders over myriad landscapes, bypasses villages, and touches upon Kanoni, a beautiful viewing spot that overlooks the densely green Pontikonissi Island.</p>\n', 1, 0, 86, '39.62', '19.92', 'corfu', 0, 1),
(2960, 1018, 'Corinth', 'Korinth, Corinthe', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Corinth is arguably one of the most strategically placed cities in the whole Mediterranean basin; the site of conquest and counter-conquest, siege and counter-siege for millennia. First it was one of the most powerful poli in ancient Greece, ruled by the formidable seafaring Corinthians, with their definitive column designs and high-perched Acropolis. Then came the Romans, and after them the Byzantines, eager to fend off barbarian tribesmen from the north.<br />\n	Today New Corinth stands just a little outside of the ancient town, rising in classic white-washed Greek facades from the deep blue of the gulf&mdash;just a stone&rsquo;s throw from the soaring citadel (Acrocorinth) and deep-cut Isthmus (Corinth Canal) that made this place so coveted throughout its tumultuous life. From here the sprawling archaeological site of the old town is easily accessible by city bus, and interested guests should be sure to ask their Corinth tourist guide for tips on the &lsquo;must see&rsquo; sites; the Temple of Apollo; the old marketplace; the crumbling Roman Odeum.<br />\n	Afterwards, get comfortable in one of the seaside bars that line the town&rsquo;s northern fringe, dipping your toes in and out of the Med as you drink, or perhaps ponder that possible bungee jump into the nearby Corinth Canal.</p>\n', 1, 0, 86, '37.94', '22.93', 'corinth', 0, 1),
