(3111, 1087, 'Kuala Lumpur', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Kuala Lumpur is a bubbling hodgepodge of big business structures and classy gastronomic joints, punctuated by wide, green urban spaces and busy boulevards lined with leaning palms. It&rsquo;s one of the self-proclaimed commerce hubs of Southeast Asia, proudly electric and advanced in its reworking of the oft-considered Asian traditionalism.<br />\n	Today, many visitors are awed by the city&rsquo;s hedonistic nightlife, while others are pleasantly surprised by the veritable array of foodstuffs on offer in the restaurants or street side market stalls. But it&rsquo;s all part-and-parcel in this buzzing metropolis, where the overarching blanket of character is woven from the threads of unbridled multiculturalism and international investment to boot.<br />\n	While the iconic Petronas Towers are perhaps the most enduring image of KL&rsquo;s modernity on the skyline, the city is now heaving with new constructions and other truly daunting high rise commercial centres. Consequently, many a Kuala Lumpur tourist guide would recommend one of the city&rsquo;s rooftop &lsquo;sky bars&rsquo; as perhaps the best introduction to its 360-degree panorama, a great way to get acquainted with the metropolis&rsquo; undeniably immersive character that&rsquo;s much-loved for its ability to flood the senses to excess.</p>\n', 1, 0, 151, '3.16', '101.71', 'kuala-lumpur', 0, 1),
(3112, 1088, 'Bydgoszcz', '', '', 1, 0, 172, '53.12', '18.01', 'bydgoszcz', 0, 1),
(3113, 1088, 'Torun', 'Thorn', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Glorious, gothic Torun; a city whose magnificence lies in its obscurity; off-the-beaten-track and proud. Visitors come here to wander amidst the spires of the city&rsquo;s old town centre, where the main sights cluster around a pleasant central square: The great 13th-century clock tower of the Ratusz Town Hall, the grand fa&ccedil;ade of the Kamienica Pod Gwiazdą (House under the Star), the sprawling remains of the ancient Teutonic bulwarks and the grand Dąmbski Palace to name just a few.<br />\n	Another group of visitors come here on a pilgrimage to pay homage to the great Polish thinker Nicolaus Copernicus, who was reputedly born in one of the historic houses at Torun&rsquo;s heart. Reminders of Torun&rsquo;s most famous prot&eacute;g&eacute;e can be seen right throughout the city, from the sculpted epitaph in the main Cathedral to the unassuming plaque that graces the wall of his 15th-century home-come-modern museum.<br />\n	Elsewhere Torun tourist guides are quick to recommend a walk along the Vistula banks, while the city is also home to the most famous gingerbread bakeries in all of Poland, cooking up batches of tasty pierniki breads every day of the year.</p>\n', 1, 0, 172, '53.02', '18.61', 'torun', 0, 1),
