(3364, 1198, 'Lviv', 'Lvov, Lemberg, Lwów, Lvuv, Lemberik', '<p class="fr-tag" style="text-align: justify;">This undisputed touristic kingpin of western Ukraine is unlike any other city in the country. Touting a wealth of exquisite Germanic architecture, gothic churches and renaissance palaces, Lviv speaks more of Slavic traditionalism than it does of the former Soviet Union, while its distinct multiculturalism and pro-Europe vibe has made it something of a cradle of political liberalism within the country.</p><p class="fr-tag" style="text-align: justify;">Sightseeing in Lviv centres on the old town, where the bustling Market Square gives way to enchanting cobbled lanes, the Catholic landmark of the Latin Cathedral, the honorific Shevchenko Monument and the eerie Chapel of the Boim. Nearby the Lychakiv Cemetery lurks, the resting place of countless Polish and Ukrainian luminaries since the 18<sup>th</sup> century. Lviv tour guides also recommend enjoying a show at the world-famous Lviv Opera and Ballet, or delving into the town’s wealth of great museums, which range from the city’s branch of the Ukraine National Museum, to the curious Pharmacy Museum on Drukarska.</p><p class="fr-tag" style="text-align: justify;">After dark the city transforms itself, with the locals going underground to enjoy potent vodka in the shadowy corners of the city’s subterranean watering holes, or steaming plates of Slavic dumplings amidst traditional timber interiors, set against the soundtrack of Euro pop until the very early hours.</p>', 1, 0, 218, '49.83', '24.00', 'lviv', 0, 1),
