(3369, 1203, 'Madaba', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Madaba was first mentioned in the Bible at the time of Exodus, about 1200 BC.&nbsp; Modern Madaba is built on an artificial mound that conceals the remains of much earlier sites.&nbsp; This &ldquo;City of Mosaics&rdquo; showcases hundreds of mosaics from the 5<sup>th</sup> through the 7<sup>th</sup> centuries that can be seen at Madaba&rsquo;s churches and homes including the 6<sup>th</sup> century Mosaic Map of Jerusalem and the Holy Land in St. George&rsquo;s Church.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Madaba is a small town and one can walk or catch a taxi to the places of interest such as the Madaba Archaelogical Museum, Madaba Folklore Museum, Shrine of the Beheading of Saint John the Baptist, an Iron Age Fortification Wall, and the Dolmens at Al Fayha.&nbsp;</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Your Madaba visitor guide will tell you that, like the town itself, the restaurants embrace different cultures and tastes; look forward to Jordanian hospitality and delicious food.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Day trips can be made by taxi or bus to nearby places of interest such as Mount Nebo, where the bible says Moses went to see the Promised Land; one can also see the Dead Sea, Jericho and even the hills overlooking Jerusalem.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Also nearby is Wadi Jadid, a field of dolmens, some of which are 5,000 years old and the thermal mineral springs of Hammamat Ma&#39;in.&nbsp; Several buildings, churches and stone arches still stand in the walled ruined city of Umm Ar-Rasas; however the main attraction is outside the city walls at the Church of St. Stephen where you will see a perfectly preserved mosaic floor dating back to 718 AD.</p>\n', 1, 0, 107, '31.72', '35.79', 'madaba', 0, 1),
(3370, 1204, 'Madang', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Prospective travellers to this provincial capital on the edge of Papua New Guinea&rsquo;s north-eastern coast will no doubt have heard tales of its fabled beauty, whispered by the odd veteran visitor or oft-quoted in the travel guides. Well, they aren&rsquo;t wrong; Madang really is that melange of verdant coastlands and hidden beaches backed by leaning palms; Madang really does feather its way out into the South Pacific in curved coves of sand and azure water.<br />\n	Today though, the centre of town also hums with bubbling goods markets, laden with farmers&rsquo; stalls touting fresh produce from the highlands towards the centre of the country, while regular tours depart for nearby Krangket Island and the various World War II sites that pepper the north coast.<br />\n	Many a Madang tour guide will recommend a visit, or even better a home stay at one of the villages around to enjoy the area&rsquo;s laid-back flavour and even sight the occasional flying fox, while indulging in a round of bird watching. But whether you come here to relax, to rummage around the historic sites or simply to wallow between the waterways and green coast, it will be well worth your time!</p>\n', 1, 0, 169, '-5.23', '145.79', 'madang', 0, 1),
