(3687, 1307, 'Menia', 'al Minya, El Minya, Minia', '<p class="fr-tag" style="text-align: justify;">Straddling the borderlands between Upper and Lower Egypt, the city of Minya—like so many peppering the banks of the Nile here—boasts a history of more than five millennia, and a story that’s entwined with the Pharaohs of the Old Kingdom, Islamic caliphates and traders from imperial Britain and the Levant alike. </p><p class="fr-tag" style="text-align: justify;">As most Minya tour guides will tell you, the city is the perfect base for exploring the wealth of ancient sites that pepper the Nile basin in Central Egypt. Consequently, many of the visitors here opt straight away for excursions to the ruins of the one-time Egyptian capital at Tel Al Amarana, the eerie tombs of Beni Hassan to the south, or the lingering Roman relics at Tuna Al Jebel, not to mention the various Christian monasteries at places like Abu Al Barsha and Abu Hamas. </p><p class="fr-tag" style="text-align: justify;">Minya itself though is a pleasant affair of breezy avenues and old stuccoed frontispieces left over from a cotton boom of the 20<sup>th</sup> century. A laid-back vibe dominates throughout, perpetuated by friendly local traders and university students, who congregate on the walkways of the town’s pretty corniche over rounds of Egyptian tea.</p>', 1, 0, 62, '28.09', '30.75', 'menia', 0, 1),
(3688, 1308, 'Shebin El Kom', 'Shibin al Kawm, Shibin al Kom, Shibin el Kom, Shebeen el Koom', '', 1, 0, 62, '30.56', '31.00', 'shebin-el-kom', 0, 1),
(3689, 1309, 'Merida', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Flying 1,600 meters above sea level, on the high plateaus of the Venezuelan Andes, the post-colonial town of Merida is the country&rsquo;s self-proclaimed hub of adventure tourism and outdoors pursuits. And the epithet is truly deserved, with the town placed just some 15 kilometres from the soaring, rugged summit of Pico Bol&iacute;var, entirely enclosed by the mountains and valleys of the greater Merida State.<br />\n	There&rsquo;s opportunities here to paraglide, mountain bike and explore the craggy canyons of the Andes, so if you&rsquo;ve got a taste for adrenaline, then be sure to ask your Merida tourist guide for tips on the best adventure operators in town. If not, then don&rsquo;t despair, because Merida&rsquo;s iconic Telef&eacute;rico gondola is at hand to help&mdash;transporting view-hungry guests to the tip of Pico Espejo nearby.<br />\n	Aside from Merida&rsquo;s outdoorsy spirit, the town also boasts a lively character that&rsquo;s only boosted by its large university population and smattering of Venezuelan cocktail bars, while there&rsquo;s really nothing quite as enchanting as the stone-built church of Juan Felix Sanchez that lingers just outside of town.</p>\n', 1, 0, 225, '8.40', '-71.13', 'merida', 0, 1),
