(4440, 1535, 'Thunder Bay', 'Port Arthur, Fort Williams', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Thunder Bay, located on the shores of Lake Superior, the largest fresh water lake in the world, is a body of water formed by the finger like projection of the Sibley Bay peninsula into the lake.&nbsp;&nbsp; When viewed from the city, the Sibley Bay peninsula resembles a sleeping giant, a view endorsed by Ojibway Legend and officially engraved on Thunder Bay&rsquo;s coat of arms.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	The Sibley Bay&rsquo;s rugged hills and mesas are part of The Sleeping Giant Provincial Park, an iconic natural reserve that is also a gateway to Canada&rsquo;s great outdoors. &nbsp;Thunder Bay is where wilderness enthusiasts go to for getting outfitted before setting off fishing in one of the tens of thousands of lakes of Ontario, hiking and biking down wilderness trails or setting off on camping and photography jaunts to experience the wildlife of the area. Your Thunder Bay Tour guide will put you through the fantastic experience of walking across a 300 ft. suspension Bridge at Eagle Canyon, or taking a day trip to the Kalabeka Falls, not to miss a step back into the past at the Fort William Historical Park.&nbsp;</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Thunder Bay is an important shipping port on the Saint Lawrence Seaway and is also a popular stop for Great Lakes cruises. This beautiful area also called the &ldquo;Canadian Lakehead&rdquo; has lots to offer day visitors and those enjoying a longer stay.</p>\n', 1, 0, 35, '48.42', '-89.28', 'thunder-bay', 0, 1),
