(4952, 1669, 'Qena', 'Qina, Kena', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	While Qena is perhaps famed as the home of one of Egypt&rsquo;s best-preserved Ptolemaic temples and Nile-side archaeological posts outside of Luxor, it also has the region&rsquo;s most important Islamic religious sites and points of pilgrimage. These are the old Maghreb and Sheikh el-Qenawi mosques that pepper the town, the latter found towering over the central squares here with its whitewashed minarets and opulent domes.<br />\n	Ever since the construction of the Wadi Qena, this provincial capital is also a favourite stopover for travellers making their way eastwards to the sprawling resorts of the Red Sea, as they head to its market to stock up on the famous &ldquo;kullars&rdquo;, porous water bottles made of local clay.<br />\n	Qena tour guides would then advice visitors to make a jaunt down the banks of the river to the sprawling ruins of the Temple of Hathor in Dendera , which is still hailed as one of the most undamaged religious sites of the Egyptian 4th century, and supposedly concealing a wealth of even more ancient Khufu structures below.</p>\n', 1, 0, 62, '26.15', '32.72', 'qena', 0, 1),
