(4963, 1677, 'Montreal', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Montreal&rsquo;s high tourism rate is definitely a result of its&rsquo; universal appeal. College students flock here for its&rsquo; party scene, while couples relish in Old Montreal&rsquo;s romantic water view and cobblestone streets; foodies indulge in the richest French food this side of Paris, and families head to the city&rsquo;s unique attractions. Known for its&rsquo; museums, Montreal&rsquo;s Biodome depicts four different ecosystems, complete with a humid jungle where monkeys roam. Meanwhile, downtown Montreal booms with bachelor party-worthy nightlife and trendy shops. In summer months, restaurants&rsquo; diners overflow onto the sidewalk verandas, and bitterly cold winters welcome the city&rsquo;s underground streets and glistening snowfalls.<br />\n	Regardless of season, the public transportation is widespread and accessible, allowing tourists to visit the city&rsquo;s three-building casino on Ile Notre-Dame before heading uptown to McGill University&rsquo;s sprawling campus. While anyone will be able to point you to easily available public transport to visit the majestic Notre Dame Basilica, your Montreal tour guide will remind you the city&rsquo;s predominant language is French. So stopping and asking for directions may find you in a predicament with a local less learned in English.&nbsp;</p>\n', 1, 0, 35, '45.52', '-73.57', 'montreal', 0, 1),
(4964, 1677, 'Quebec', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Rising dramatically from the northern banks of the Saint Lawrence River, the cityscape of Quebec casts a fairy-tale silhouette of chateau turrets and gothic spires, all encompassed by the oldest city walls in North America and some of the most enchanting urban architecture in all of Canada. No wonder this one has a reputation for handsomeness.<br />\n	Ask any Quebec tour guide and they&rsquo;ll tell you, there really is nowhere better to start your travels here than in the heart of Vieux-Qu&eacute;bec&mdash;the beating touristic kingpin of the city, where winding cobbled lanes abut grandiose city halls and Old World poutine eateries. Here, it&rsquo;s impossible to miss the looming figure of Chateau Frontenac, soaring above the exquisite Parliament Buildings and riverside Dufferin Terrace.<br />\n	But don&rsquo;t be deceived by Quebec&rsquo;s pretty veneer, because this town is no museum piece to the colonial age. Rather, it boasts a throbbing, student-led nightlife and a buzzing international bar scene on the Rue Saint-Jean, while there&rsquo;s oodles of high-energy pursuits on offer, from skiing on the inner-city Plains of Abraham, to chiselling ice sculptures at the annual Winter Carnival.</p>\n', 1, 0, 35, '46.82', '-71.23', 'quebec', 0, 1),
