(5103, 1686, 'Jaipur', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Hailed as the Pink City for its endless array of proudly vibrant and colourful architecture, Jaipur is one of the touristic gems of India; a truly heady destination that combines all the wealth of the country&rsquo;s historical and cultural past, with its buzzing, commercial modernity.<br />\n	Set amidst the rugged and arid valleys on the outskirts of the Great Indian Desert, Jaipur tour guides are sure to offer you a unique and breath-taking introduction to this city. It&rsquo;s a place where hilltop forts and a blend of Rajput and Mughal palaces cast their gaze across the horizon and the glow of the setting sun adds an ethereal Eastern charm that&rsquo;s almost unspeakable in its uniqueness.<br />\n	But away from the palace complexes and regal UNESCO sites, Jaipur, also India&rsquo;s first planned city also oozes with the raw and human character that is India&rsquo;s own prerogative. Visitors can explore a warren of traditional marketplaces and sprawling suburbs, to come away with lighter pockets, colourful mementos and hearts filled with the warmth of authentic Indian hospitality.</p>\n', 1, 0, 100, '26.92', '75.80', 'jaipur', 0, 1),
(5104, 1686, 'Jodhpur', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Jodhpur is a thriving historic city located at the edge of the Thar Desert. The city boasts traditional cuisine, fine handicrafts, rich carpets and marble.&nbsp; The energy in Jodhpur is warm and colorful, thumping with the vibrant passion of folk song and dance.<br />\n	Jodhpur has multiple epithets as the &ldquo;Sun City&rdquo; and the &ldquo;Blue City&rdquo;. &ldquo;Sun City&rdquo; because of the bright sun that shines down on it all year through, and &ldquo;Blue City&rdquo; to address the blue painted houses that outline the fort of Mehrangarh.&nbsp;<br />\n	Many traditional festivals can be attended throughout the year, including Nag Panchami, Marwar festivals, Nav Sati, Gangaur, Veerpuri fair, Holi, Diwali, among others.&nbsp; Ask for the assistance of Jodhpur tourist guides with travel during these crowded festival times.<br />\n	Polo is the very popular royal sport in Jodhpur, and equestrian events are popularly held as traditional sport. Trivia Alert: the word &ldquo;Jodhpurs&rdquo; defining the riding breeches used when riding a horse derives it etymology from this city.<br />\n	The Fort of Mehrangah, one of the largest forts in India is the most popular attraction in Jodhpur. Encompassing palaces with intricate latticework, temples and vast gardens, it is very easy to get lost in time and the splendour of this charming fort.&nbsp;&nbsp; Jaswant Thada is a white marble memorial temple, an easy walk down from the fort. The romantic Umaid Bhawan is still home to the royal family, which resides in a part of it; the rest of it has been converted into a luxury hotel. Having paid homage to the landmarks, enjoy the city for its temples that liberally dot the cityscape, haggle at the colourful bazaars for bandhni , silver jewellery and your own pair of &ldquo;jodhpuris&rdquo; and definitely get a taste of the mouthwatering &ldquo;mithais&rdquo; and savoury items that will leave you asking for more!</p>\n', 1, 0, 100, '26.29', '73.02', 'jodhpur', 0, 1),
(5105, 1686, 'Kota', '', '', 1, 0, 100, '25.18', '75.83', 'kota', 0, 1),
(5106, 1686, 'Bikaner', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Located in the bitter wilderness of the far northwest corners of India, Bikaner surprises with its burst of colour and vibrancy amidst the sand dunes. An old princely state lovingly built by the Rajputs in the 1400s, it is easy to get a whiff of its medieval splendour at the fabulous Junagarh fort, also its biggest attraction. An in-house museum at Junagarh tracks the life and glorious times of the royal family as do other glamorous palaces in the city, some converted into opulent hotels catering to the upper echelons of visitors. Narrow streets built with the intent to protect against frequent sandstorms run through the old walled city, while temples dot the entire landscape uniformly, the most popular being the Karni Mata temple for its worship of rats, clearly a unique ritual even in India.<br />\n	All over Bikaner camels easily share space with motorized vehicles, often being the preferred mode of transport in the desert intensive parts about and out of town. In the winter months, many a Bikaner tour guide would recommend a Desert Safari in the Thar Desert, an out and out exhilarating experience that will leave visitors with memories of achingly beautiful dunes interspersed with colourful villages.</p>\n', 1, 0, 100, '28.03', '73.32', 'bikaner', 0, 1),
(5107, 1686, 'Ajmer', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Deep in the vast and popular tourist Indian State of Rajasthan lies the spiritual city of Ajmer. Holy to both Muslims and Hindus, Ajmer was established in the 7<sup>th</sup> century and is home to religious shrines, forts and traditional Rajasthani cuisine.<br />\n	The Dargah Sharif of Khwaja Muinuddin Chisti would be the first point of veneration in any Ajmer tourist guide. The hallowed shrine draws not only Muslims but also people from all faiths to the sufi saint&rsquo;s tomb for blessings. The Nasiyan ji Temple, a sacred Jain temple mesmerizes with its gold creations and intricate work.&nbsp; Don&rsquo;t miss a visit to Taragarh Fort, one of the oldest hill forts in India for an enchanting view of Ajmer during sunset. Take a relaxing stroll at the gardens by the 900-year-old Anasagar Lake or browse through the local markets enticing one and all with their colourful curios.<br />\n	For that added dose of spirituality head over to Pushkar to pay your respects at the Brahma Temple. Vastly popular for its annual fair, Pushkar is a short drive away enough to make a day trip and return to Ajmer just in time for that mouth watering Rajasthani thali!</p>\n', 1, 0, 100, '26.45', '74.64', 'ajmer', 0, 1),
(5108, 1686, 'Udaipur', '', '<p>\n	The many lakes of Udaipur surrounded by picturesque hills has earned this romantic city multiple epithets of&nbsp; &ldquo;City of Lakes&rdquo; and &ldquo;Venice of the East&rdquo;<br />\n	The majestic City Palace is home to a number of palaces, gardens, and monuments juxtaposing multiple architectural styles. Lake Pichola provides a natural boundary to the City Palace and holds in its lap, the famous and romantic Lake Palace.&nbsp; The size and architecture of the Lake palace as it reflects on the blue water of the Lake Pichola is breathtaking, especially at the sunset hour. Don&rsquo;t miss a boat ride in the man made Fateh Sagar Lake to visit the Nehru Park, one of its islands.<br />\n	Udaipur has a calm and&nbsp; easy vibe to it, making it a nice getaway from the more hectic surrounding cities in India.&nbsp; However, the festivals in Udaipur are lively, and many visitors flock to the city to partake in the lakeside events.&nbsp; Udaipur tourist guides confirm that Udaipur has been the backdrop for numerous movies, including the James Bond film &ldquo;Octopussy&rdquo; and off late a popular site destination weddings for couples from all over the globe!</p>\n', 1, 0, 100, '24.58', '73.69', 'udaipur', 0, 1),
