(5592, 1866, 'Shkoder', 'Scutari, Skutari, Skadar', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Between the formidable bluff rise of Rozafa Castle on the city&rsquo; south-western edge to the jagged peaks of the Albanian Alps in the north, the lakeside city of Shkoder is one of the country&rsquo;s undisputed gems of history, culture and natural beauty.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	The earliest settlements here have been dated to around the 3<sup>rd</sup> century BC, making Shkoder one of Europe&rsquo;s oldest metropolitan centres. In more recent decades the town has experienced a turbulent course of annexation, occupation and liberation, but has emerged from it all with a newfound flair and character. Recent renovations have given the downtown centres of Sheshi and Kol Idromeno a pleasant European feel, complete with bustling cafes and cobbled side streets, while the Molo Promenade is the perfect place to go for relaxing walks along the riverside.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	The city is famed for its bike-friendly infrastructure, and taking two-wheeled tours around the various churches and mosques has become one of the most popular activities here. For shoppers and souvenir seekers, Shkoder Tour guides recommend the Bazaar of the Artisans near the entrance to town, a treasure trove not to be missed.</p>\n', 1, 0, 6, '42.07', '19.51', 'shkoder', 0, 1),
(5593, 1868, 'Siauliai', 'Schaulen, Shiauliai, Showli', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Siauliai in Lithuania can be as local as it gets, as well as be the perfect urban exploration option for travellers who&rsquo;ve already ticked off the country&rsquo;s other major cities and now want something more original and authentic, through-and-through.<br />\n	To gauge the city&rsquo;s local character, start by taking a stroll past the laid-back coffee houses and beer bars of Vilniaus Street a.k.a &ldquo;The Boulevard&rdquo;, also Siauliai&rsquo;s central modern core. Be sure to ask your Siauliai tourist guide for tips on the curious array of architecture, from the magnificent Cathedral of Siauliai with its tall white tower and the elegant Villa of Chaim Frenkel that have lingered here since the town&rsquo;s destruction in World War Two, to the Sundial Square symbolising the city&rsquo;s very foundation.<br />\n	In the winter, be sure to make a trip to the mysterious Hill of Crosses to the north of town (best done in the snow), a pilgrimage site where masses of religious icons protrude from the ground. While in the summer, there are the city&rsquo;s lakes Rekyva, Talk&scaron;a, and Ginkunai, and their concomitant green parks and water sports to enjoy.</p>\n', 1, 0, 127, '55.93', '23.32', 'siauliai', 0, 1),
(5594, 1869, 'Sibiu', 'Hermannstadt, Nagyszeben', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Affluent and charming Sibiu sits in the very heartlands of Romanian Transylvania, rising in terraces of red-tiled roofs, webs of cobbled roadways and lines of pretty medieval homes against the white peaks of the Cindrel Mountains. With its long history of Germanic influence and Austro-Hungarian rule, the town exudes a noticeably western vibe, while doing well to cling to Romanian traditionalism between the steaming bowls of Ciorba broth and the sprawling national collections of the Brukenthal Museum.<br />\n	Anyone interested in unravelling the histories that so alluringly ooze from every apse and archway of the old town here should ask their Sibiu tourist guide for walking tours of the medieval citadel and the Germanic buildings of the upper and lower centres, or the stories behind the Liars&rsquo; Bridge. There is then an open air museum that is a must see amongst the collection of the city&rsquo;s informative museums, an exceedingly active cultural scene churning out festivals, theatre and exhibitions, and the cafes by the squares that offer ample opportunity to have a chat with Sibiu&rsquo;s laid back locals. Those interested in heading further afield can look to Sibiu as a great jump off point for exploring sylvan Transylvania, with its hilltop castles and mysterious churches; or make their way to the Paltinis ski resort, Romania&rsquo;s highest, and a veritable mecca for budget skiers looking for a spot in the Southern Carpathians.</p>\n', 1, 0, 181, '45.79', '24.13', 'sibiu', 0, 1),
