(5633, 1879, 'Silhat', 'Sylhet', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Deep in the north-eastern hills of Bangladesh, the city of Silhat is sprawled over the undulating hillsides of the Surma Valley. Affluent and developing fast, it&rsquo;s become a real &lsquo;must see&rsquo; on the Bangladeshi circuit, offering an altogether different natural backdrop than many other metropolitan areas in the country.<br />\n	Here, the rice field topography and thick rain forests create some breath-taking panoramas, while the unique winter flood plains of the Silhat haors provide a breeding ground for migrating birds that come from as far north as Siberia to escape the cold. If you&rsquo;re looking to experience the raw nature of Silhat, head to the Tamabil-Jaflong outpost, which has great views of the Indian waterfalls north of the border, or visit the Sree Mangal tea gardens, the largest of their kind in the world.<br />\n	Silhat is also known for the yearly Sufi pilgrimages that flock here to honour the Shahs Jalal and Paran, and it&rsquo;s possible to visit their respective shrines closer to town. These are just a few examples of Silhat&rsquo;s important position as a cultural and religious kingpin in the region, while the central clock and other architectural sites are also worth a visit.&nbsp;</p>\n', 1, 0, 18, '24.90', '91.87', 'silhat', 1, 1),
