(5722, 1921, 'Ouarzazate', 'Warzazat', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Sitting on a plateau near the High Atlas Mountains lies the Kasbah of Ouarzazate, its brick orange mud exterior blending in with the surrounding desert. For many tourists wishing to explore the desert and Draa Valley, Ouarzazate is used as a base but this friendly town has a vibrancy and life of its own.<br />\n	Allow one of the local Ouarzazate Travel guides to organise a tour to the Atlas Film Studio, the largest of its kind in the world where the classic film Lawrence of Arabia, Star Wars and Body of Lies was filmed. Filled with many historical buildings and sites, visit the Museum of the Liberation Army of Ouarzazate and the Saint Theresa Church, its bronze bell recalling a time when the French Army built the Tizi-n-Tichka Pass. Stroll around the Al-Mouahidine Square towards the bustling Ouarzazate Center Market finding some relief from the intense heat with a glass of mint tea or freshly squeezed orange juice and one of the delicious pastries filled with honey, cinnamon and nuts. The large man-made Al-Mansour Ad-Dahbi Lake transforms the desert landscape becoming an oasis for fishing or a starting point for one of the many hiking trails.</p>\n', 1, 0, 131, '30.92', '-6.90', 'ouarzazate', 0, 1),
(5723, 1921, 'Tinghir', 'Tingir', '', 1, 0, 131, '31.52', '-5.53', 'tinghir', 0, 1),
(5724, 1921, 'Zagora', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	As one of the last bastions of Moroccan civilisation before the great swathes of Sahara sand dunes in the south, Zagora is a town entirely enveloped by the raw nature of northern Africa. A now legendary signpost in the town stands as testimony to its remoteness. Reading &ldquo;Tombouctou:52 days&rdquo;, it&rsquo;s the last spot the more intrepid traveller will pose for a photograph before entering the desert.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Zagora&rsquo;s multifarious roles as weekend venue for local food bazaars, annual Sufi pilgrimage destination and overnight stop-off for traders on the cross-desert trail have given it a curiously dynamic character. So, while visitors coming here to catch a glimpse of authentic Moroccan country life won&rsquo;t be disappointed, the myriad of other cultural and religious influences at play are truly alluring in their diversity.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	So close to the desert, a Zagora tour guide will advise those looking to make the ubiquitous Moroccan camel ride over the dunes that the town is the perfect place for such an adventure. The imposing plateau of Jebel Zagora Mountain that looms nearby has ample hiking opportunities and an impressive ruined Almoravid castle that makes braving the heat entirely worth it.&nbsp;</p>\n', 1, 0, 131, '30.33', '-5.86', 'zagora', 0, 1),
