(5796, 1948, 'Buea', '', '<p class="fr-tag" style="text-align: justify;">Clinging tenaciously to the volcanic ridges of Mount Cameroon, high-perched Buea first came to prominence as the capital of German Kamerun in the early 20<sup>th</sup> century. The town of today is still peppered with the dilapidating remnants of that period, rising up in age-stained neo-classical frontispieces between the tin-shack conglomerations and haphazard mountain homes of the city’s outer districts and sprawling market bazaars. </p><p class="fr-tag" style="text-align: justify;">But despite this one’s curious backstory courtesy of the Kaiser and von Puttkamer, most travellers who make their way here today, do so in search of a Buea tour guide to take them up to the soaring heights of Muont Cameroon. One of Africa’s highest volcanoes, it rises above the city in a medley of otherworldly craters and protrusions, ringed with metamorphic lava flows and criss-crossed by some truly breath-taking hiking trails. Below, the resort town of Limbe beckons too—a place of volcanic beaches coloured with black sand, a stately green garden, and a sprawling wildlife park echoing with the calls of baboons and gorillas.</p>', 1, 0, 44, '4.16', '9.23', 'buea', 0, 1),
(5797, 1949, 'Suez', 'as Suways, Sues', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Clustered haphazardly around the southern mouth of the Suez Canal, this namesake city is a tumultuous manifestation of Egyptian industry and mechanisation run amok. With most of its historic sights destroyed during the fracases of the 20th century, it&rsquo;s now a town of looming cranes, sprawling concrete complexes and traffic-laden roadways smothered; more of a fascinating image of the country in motion.<br />\n	While Suez is not a tourist haven, there are excellent seafood meals to indulge in, and Ahwas to visit and interact with the locals. Most Suez tour guides will recommend a jaunt to the bustling market squares of the Arbaeen District, where local desert dwellers come to tout their wares amidst the fray of the city. Others will direct travellers to the sprawling harboursides of Port Taufiq, where it&rsquo;s possible to watch colossal tankers gliding north from the Indian Ocean.</p>\n', 1, 0, 62, '29.98', '32.54', 'suez', 0, 1),
