(6263, 2129, 'Utrecht', '', '<p class="fr-tag" style="text-align: justify;">Sitting on its winding web of charming canals at equidistance from The Hague and Amsterdam alike, the city of Utrecht remains a real metropolitan Jewel of the Netherlands. Amongst its pretty medieval streets and beguiling array of gothic architecture, one of the country’s largest student populations lives, works and plays. This of course implies there are oodles of hip bars, cool cafes, thumping clubs and stylish drinking dives on offer, all alive with Euro-pop, frothy Belgian brews, and buzzing <em>al fresco </em>drinking terraces that poke their way out over the plazas at De Neude, or the docks at Oudegracht. No visitor here can miss the soaring Dom Tower, standing aloft atop the foundations of the ancient Roman fort that first founded the city, while most Utrecht tour guides will also recommend spying out the De Stijl architecture of the Rietveld Schroder House, the interesting collections of the Speelklok and Railway Museum, or the leafy parklands of Lepelenburg , Wilhelminapark and Botanic gardens, where locals can be found chatting the days away during the summer.</p>', 1, 0, 159, '52.10', '5.11', 'utrecht', 0, 1),
(6264, 2130, 'Kanpur', '', '', 1, 0, 100, '26.47', '80.33', 'kanpur', 0, 1),
(6265, 2130, 'Lucknow', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Think of an Indian city where emphasis is put on etiquette, nawabi (read regal) ways, a multicultural lifestyle imbued with hospitality, and melt in your mouth kebabs, and you&rsquo;ve found yourself in Lucknow, spread out majestically on the banks of the Gomti river. With a historical significance dating back to the mythical days of Ram&rsquo;s reign, this city derived its distinct cultural and physical identity under the Mughal patronage and was even courted by the British after the famous Siege of Lucknow in 1857. The labyrinth at the huge and impressive Bara Imambara , the Chattar Manzil, Rumi Darwaza, &nbsp;Chota Imambara and the Clock Tower are significant examples of Indo Islamic architecture as well its experiments with the European &nbsp;style to fuse together a completely new architectural style unique to this city.<br />\n	The capital of Uttar Pradesh, the most populous state of India has seen malls sporting brands mushrooming all over the city. For the authentic flavour go local; your Lucknow tour guide will help you pick out a piece of chikan apparel, select your favourite ittar (perfume), tuck into tunde ke kebabs followed by a handful of rewari in the local market places of Aminabad, Hazratganj, Janpath or Chowk.</p>\n', 1, 0, 100, '26.85', '80.92', 'lucknow', 0, 1),
(6266, 2130, 'Agra', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Agra&rsquo;s historical role as one of the kingpins of the Mughal Empire has gifted it the pride of place that it now enjoys on the typical tourist trail through India. Much visited and heavily photographed, none could be forgiven for choosing to forgo the enchanting Taj Mahal or wealth of other architectural relics that now stand here as a testimony to the previous grandeur of the Indian subcontinent.<br />\n	Designated by UNESCO way back in 1983, the pearly-white mausoleum of the Taj Mahal is now unsurprisingly the touted site by any Agra tour guide, while the Red Fort, also a UNESCO site just to the northwest is another veritable gem of the state of Uttar Pradesh. Both of these occupy spots on the banks of the Yamuna River, the iconic natural vena cava of the city as a whole, where the emperor Shahjahan had ambitiously proposed another Taj Mahal, this time in black. This project remained sadly unfulfilled.<br />\n	If you&rsquo;re lucky enough to be able to stay in Agra for a few days, then consider branching out to some of the other nearby points of interest. Spots like the 16th century ruined metropolis of Fatehpur Sikri, and the boisterously colourful Glass and Bangles Bazaar at Ferozabad are well within the reach of a single-day excursion.</p>\n', 1, 0, 100, '27.19', '78.01', 'agra', 0, 1),
(6267, 2130, 'Ghaziabad', '', '', 1, 0, 100, '28.66', '77.41', 'ghaziabad', 0, 1),
