(6610, 2213, 'Cape Town', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Cape Town is a city that is filled with vibrant tastes, sounds, color, creativity and is often regarded as the quintessential hub of South Africa. Slotting in as the second largest city in South Africa, Cape Town is located towards the south-west of the country, and is the most southern city in the African Continent. The city is highlighted by several remarkable sites such as the majestic Cape Winelands and the towns of Stellenbosch and Paarl.<br />\n	If you&rsquo;re visiting Africa, a visit to Cape Town should be at the top of your itinerary as there is so much to do and see including exciting events, activities and attractions. According to many Cape Town tour guide services, this city is easy to, fun and simple to navigate, and boasts an excellent transportation system. Dubbed as South Africa&rsquo;s &ldquo;Mother City&rdquo;, Cape Town has something in store for all ages and travelers such as exploring Table Mountain, the wild Cape Points and Boulders, the magnificent V&amp;A Waterfront and the plethora of underwater adventures.<br />\n	For those visiting this city for a short break, grab a pass on a Red Bus Tour, which will whisk you away to a number of points of interest to include St Georges Cathedral, the Cape Town Convention Centre, Winchester Mansions Hotel, St Johns Road and President Hotel.&nbsp;</p>\n', 1, 0, 234, '-33.93', '18.46', 'cape-town', 0, 1),
(6611, 2213, 'George', 'Thembalethu', '<p class="fr-tag" style="text-align: justify;">Situated along the pretty stretches of South Africa’s Garden Route, just a stone’s throw inland from the rolling swells of the Indian Ocean and the beaches of the Western Cape, the well-to-do city of George has established itself as an enterprising, entrepreneurial hub of business travel, conferencing and eco-tourism. </p><p class="fr-tag" style="text-align: justify;">As the sixth-oldest city in the country, George also boasts a long and enthralling history, and touts the pretty Dutch Reformed Moederkerk on Mead Street, its own local museum complex (which includes the acclaimed Outeniqua Transport Museum), and South Africa’s oldest Catholic church to prove it. </p><p class="fr-tag" style="text-align: justify;">Looming on the edges of town, visitors will also discover the Outeniqua Mountains, which throw up great safari opportunities, some excellent golf courses, and the iconic hiking trails of the Outeniqua route. George tour guides also often recommend taking a trip to the nearby beaches, which range from the sheltered Herolds Bay to the surfing stretches of Victoria in the east.</p>', 1, 0, 234, '-33.95', '22.45', 'george', 0, 1),
(6612, 2213, 'Worcester', 'eVostile, Evostile', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Nestled behind walls and walls of spikey mountains and looming massifs at the heart of the Western Cape, the country town of Worcester ticks over to the sounds of rustling grape vines and &lsquo;howzat&rsquo; cricket cries.<br />\n	It&rsquo;s perhaps primarily known for its place at the heart of the famous cellar door trail of the Cape Winelands, boasting its own tasting route of no fewer than 11 vineyards. But the delicacies don&rsquo;t stop there either, because amidst the pretty Dutch colonial homes and old railway buildings of the 19th century, visitors can also find award-winning olive farms and classic Karoo bistros touting regional lamb cuts and in-house whites and reds to boot.<br />\n	And once your palate is overloaded with flavours, and you simply can&rsquo;t take any more of those breath-taking panoramas encompassing the snow-tipped Hex River Mountains and passes of Du Toitskloof, then be sure to ask your Worcester tour guide about the Kleinplasie Living Open Air Museum, where it&rsquo;s possible to unravel the unexpected European threads of this mountain city&rsquo;s curious human history.</p>\n', 1, 0, 234, '-33.64', '19.44', 'worcester', 0, 1),
(6613, 2213, 'Stellenbosch', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Nestled deep in the wine valleys of the western South African Cape, Stellenbosch is surrounded by fertile fields of verdant green sprouting row upon row of famous vine and regal oak. Not a wonder it&rsquo;s easy to believe that it was the soil, and the terrior that brought the first settlers to this truly picturesque corner of the world. Start your look around by surveying the downtown and its rich collection of unique Cape Dutch architecture; those interested in unravelling the history of this colonial outpost a little further will do well at the Stellenbosch Museum and Powder House on the Braak. Tap into the city&rsquo;s cultural buzz at its incessant music spots, populated by its incumbent communities and students from its famous university.<br />\n	The biggest draw of this region however, is its wine, and aficionados should be sure to ask their Stellenbosch tourist guide about all the available excursions to the cellar doors that pepper the surroundings of this oak lined town. Nature lovers and outdoor enthusiasts alike can look forward to joining the locals in tapping the neighbouring mountains, forests and valleys to indulge in a medley of pursuits from hiking to mountain biking and golfing.</p>\n', 1, 0, 234, '-33.92', '18.86', 'stellenbosch', 0, 1),
(6614, 2213, 'Mosselbay', 'Mossel Bay, Aliwal Suid, Aliwal South, Mosselbaai', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Situated on the Garden Route, the picturesque town of Mossel Bay is a beautiful holiday resort with sun streaked yellow beaches lapped at by warm waters of the Indian Ocean. The explorer Bartholomew Dias first threw anchor in Mossel Bay in 1488 and thus was the first to start the now busy harbour of today. One would be remiss if one did not hire a professional Mossel Bay tourist guide as this historical village has a plethora of museums and places of interest. Overlooking the sea with panoramic views, the Bartholomew Dias Museum complex stretches over the sweeping Ethno- Botanical Gardens. Renowned for its great white sharks, why not go shark cage diving and see the beauty of these enormous creatures up close or snorkel amongst the reefs with the diverse range of fish and sea urchins. Take that hike down the St Blaize Trail for incredible views of the coastline and, whale and dolphin watching. And then of course, no visit is complete without a sojourn to a game reserve for an up and close encounter with one or all of the Big 5!&nbsp;</p>\n', 1, 0, 234, '-34.17', '22.13', 'mosselbay', 0, 1),
(6615, 2213, 'Knysna', 'Khayalethu', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Enveloped by primeval woodland and arched elegantly over a seaside lagoon of the Indian Ocean, the city of Knysna has long been praised for its supreme natural beauty and prime location on the famed Garden Route of South Africa&rsquo;s Western Cape. A noticeably pleasant Mediterranean microclimate reigns through the year nurturing forests and eco reserves, overseeing hiking and biking trails, wildlife excursions through its fynbos, and even a local rastafarian community.<br />\n	Any Knysna tour guide will proudly proclaim the Knysna Heads as its most famed attraction, and the lagoon it encloses is a hotbed of aqua adventure from sea kayaking and boat charters to whale watching. The town itself has high status as a veritable golfers paradise that gets even livelier around the festivals that it hosts through the year. Culinary-orientated travellers would do well to come in mid-July, when Knysna bustles with the annual Oyster Festival, South Africa&rsquo;s largest celebration of fresh seafood, easily paired with its locally brewed beer.<br />\n	Away from the outdoorsy activities, Knysna provides a perfect seaside retreat for luxury-seekers too, and the abundance of boutique accommodations, quirky local shopping spots and independent art galleries rarely fail to deliver.</p>\n', 1, 0, 234, '-34.03', '23.06', 'knysna', 0, 1),
(6616, 2213, 'Oudtshoorn', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	The quaint town of Oudtshoorn in the Klein Karoo exudes warmth and hospitality, with a mindboggling variety of excursions to indulge in.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Your Oudtshoorn Tour guide will start your trip to the Ostrich Capital by setting up a visit to an ostrich farm. Feeding and interacting with these large eyed birds is fun but even more so is trying your hand at riding an ostrich or participating in an ostrich race! If you&rsquo;re up for even more adventure on the wild side, dive with crocodiles, get in hand shaking range with a cheetah, interact with lemurs at the Lemur Falls at Cango Wildlife Ranch, or simply go on a safari to interact with all the flora and fauna this beautifully diverse land has on offer. For nature lovers, the Cango Caves located in at the foothills of the Swartberg range are a beautiful masterpiece with naturally coloured limestone formations and yawning caverns. Don&rsquo;t miss a visit to the Swartberg Mountains for a viewing of rock paintings by the Bushmen that initially inhabited this fertile land.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	The town itself is magical as you drive through the streets and see Ostrich Palaces of Oudtshoorn built by ostrich farmers during the feather boom years. Built in varying shades of sandstone, many of these impeccably maintained opulent mansions are presently converted into guesthouses. Alongside, the dainty Victorian houses play host to restaurants and coffee shops, a welcome relief after a busy day of activities</p>\n', 1, 0, 234, '-33.58', '22.19', 'oudtshoorn', 0, 1),
