(7056, 520, 'Machu Picchu', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	If there were ever a UNESCO heritage site that needed no introduction, Machu Picchu would definitely be the one. Soaring high more than 2,400 metres above the lands of Cusco, this sprawling ancient city of the Incans now attracts nearly half a million visitors every year, who all make the fascinating trek along the ridges and tracks of the Incan Trail to behold its wonder high in the clouds. The iconic Inca trail itself could easily count itself as one of the world&rsquo;s best, overseeing subtropical jungles, lush mountains and of course smatterings of Inca icons and tunnels along the way; visitors hoping to do this should check well in advance with their Machu Picchu tourist guide about booking restrictions and requirements.<br />\n	The particular uses of the ruins are still the point of continued debate; it&rsquo;s thought that the Incans first raised Machu Picchu&rsquo;s mountain top walls in the 13th century, perhaps as a royal palace, perhaps an honorific monument to the Incan sun god. But whatever the reasons that linger beneath these mysterious ruins, the fact remains they are among the most alluring and wondrous in the whole world.</p>\n', 1, 0, 167, '-13.09', '-72.32', 'machu-picchu', 0, 1),
(7057, 905, 'Dahab', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	For many an intrepid diver making their way through the legendary scuba spots of the Sinai Peninsula, Dahab is perhaps the most-coveted mecca of them all. This small Bedouin coastal town by the Red Sea offers easy access to many of the best underwater descents in the world, from the glassfish-laden Fishbowl, to deep Gabr el Bint, filled with colourful corals and spindly gorgonians to boot. And of course, no Dahab scuba guide could possibly forget the legendary Blue Hole, arguably the most notorious dive site on the planet!<br />\n	Dahab&rsquo;s most famous draw aside, this pretty little town still wallows in its laid-back character, hosting plenty of hippies, backpackers and New Age types that come in search raw beauty and deserted beaches away from bustling Sharm el-Sheikh in the south. To them all, Dahab tour guides bring desert excursions to Bedouin tribal villages, trekking through the Sinai backcountry, Chi Gong, spiritual healing centres and yoga courses to boot, not to mention breath-taking sand stretches like those found arching their way along beautiful Masbat Bay nearby.</p>\n', 1, 0, 62, '28.51', '34.51', 'dahab', 0, 1),
(7058, 627, 'Chichester', '', '', 1, 0, 74, '50.84', '-.78', 'chichester', 0, 1),
(7059, 2361, 'Outback', '', '', 1, 0, 13, '-23.42', '+133.53', 'outback', 0, 1),
(7060, 2362, 'Budva', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	A shimmering melange of classic red-tiled villas, rugged Montenegrin cliffs, scintillating Adriatic waters, bustling town squares of cocktail bars and European caf&eacute;s, looming jet setter condominiums, tight-knit Venetian lanes and crumbling medieval fortifications; this is Budva. This kingpin of the country&rsquo;s burgeoning Budvanska Rivijera is a bubbling mix of coastal partying, high-life hedonism and classic seaside touring, largely driven by booming crowds of Russian and Balkan nouveau riche.<br />\n	Be sure to start your visit between the exquisite churches and narrow alleyways of the Stari Grad, getting your Budva tour guide to point out all the most authentic Italian bistros, and the iconic dancing girl statue on the edge of the sea. Later on, retire to the al fresco terraces of Budva&rsquo;s bustling centre, where Slavic beers rub shoulders with Mediterranean mezze to boot.<br />\n	Of course, the beaches are also to die for (if a little small and pebbly) with a lot of scope for boat trips and yacht charters to enjoy the Mediterranean sun, while the more intrepid types can look forward to a day of zip lining across the Tara Canyon or rafting down the Tara River.</p>\n', 1, 0, 134, '42.17', '18.49', 'budva', 0, 1),
(7061, 2363, 'Cetinje', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	&nbsp;Cetinje, the historical capital of Montenegro, is a place alive with the romance and mystery of a fascinating heritage. Founded in the 15th century, the city rests on a small valley surrounded by mountains including Mt Lovcen or &lsquo;Black Mountain&rsquo; after which the country of Montenegro takes its name. For climbers, this mountain&rsquo;s summit offers a challenge while a walk of 20km followed by a 460 step staircase will take you to the breath-taking monument of Njego&scaron;&rsquo;s Mausoleum.<br />\n	Pat on the ancient borderline between East and West, Cetinje has architectural wonders galore. Visit catholic churches (such as Vlaska Church), orthodox monasteries and mosques and feast your eyes on the differences in their rich and elegant designs. Cetinje is home to the Zetski Dom Royal Theatre, numerous museums and art galleries and is working towards making the historic core of the city a UNESCO world heritage site; definitely a top destination for the culture vultures of the world.</p>\n', 1, 0, 134, '42.23', '18.55', 'cetinje', 0, 1),
