(7068, 1018, 'Ancient Corinth', '', '<p class="fr-tag" style="text-align: justify;">Clutching the natural fortifications of limestone bluffs in a symphony of ancient marble edifices and Corinthian columns, this commanding old <i>polis </i>has held sway over its own isthmus of land since time immemorial. During the 5<sup>th</sup> and 4<sup>th</sup> centuries BC it was one of the major players in the Greek world, defying even the likes of Athens with its formidable navy, and taking on Sparta during the Peloponnesian War. </p><p class="fr-tag" style="text-align: justify;">Today, visitors to the site are invited to explore an extensive ruined Agora and old town, now crumbling and chipped away and juxtaposed neatly with modern-day Corinth on the edge of the Gulf just to the north. In a palimpsest of Greek and Roman architecture, sites like the Temple of Apollo and the stoa of Phillip II of Macedon stand out, along with plenty of examples of portraiture pertaining to the Imperial Cult, many of which have now been transferred to the adjoining Archaeological Museum. </p><p class="fr-tag" style="text-align: justify;">Trips out to the striking remains and soaring acropolis here can now be organised with Ancient Corinth tour guides from the nearby new town, while there are also plenty of excursion providers based in Athens, too.</p>', 1, 0, 86, '37.91', '22.88', 'ancient-corinth', 0, 1),
(7069, 1712, 'Petrópolis', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Once the summer getaway of Brazilian imperial rule, the city of Petropolis perches high in the valleys of the country&rsquo;s dramatic Range of the Organs, showcasing some of Latin America&rsquo;s curious historical architecture and enjoying one of the region&rsquo;s most hospitable year-round climates.<br />\n	Many visitors come here from Rio de Janeiro to the south, looking to explore the the Museu Imperial complex that once formed the great palace of the Dom Pedro emperors. Within lies a collection of Brazil&rsquo;s regal treasures, ranging from the great golden crown of Pedro himself, to portrait after portrait of masters from Portugal and Europe beyond.<br />\n	Don&rsquo;t leave without joining your Petropolis tour guide for a sightseeing route of the city&rsquo;s other interesting points, from the oddly Germanic Catedral de Sao Pedro de Alcantara, to the glass-fronted Palacio de Cristal. Once the history&rsquo;s ticked off, consider heading a little further afield, for a trekking tour in the Organ Hills, or to the dramatic waterfalls that lurk beneath the jungles all around.</p>\n', 1, 0, 29, '-22.30', '-43.11', 'petrpolis', 0, 1),
(7070, 2368, 'Bar', '', '<p class="fr-tag" style="text-align: justify;">Backed by a phalanx of Montenegrin mountains, the historic spot of Stari Bar sits protected by limestone peaks, some four kilometers back from the rollers of the Adriatic and the yacht-dotted jetties of the modern-day town. It’s thought that this crumbling collection of fortresses, churches and varied architecture was trodden by the Romans, and eventually touched by the Byzantines, Slavs, Serbs, Ottomans and Venetians alike before being largely abandoned to wallow in its own past. </p><p class="fr-tag" style="text-align: justify;">Today, most all Bar tour guides are based in the shiny new side of the city, which hugs the rugged coast of southern Montenegro with its blend of condominiums, pebbly coves and palm-dotted boulevards. Here, travellers are often found kicking back on the beaches of Šušanj just a short drive north of the centre, or dutifully ticking off the quirky superlative of the oldest olive tree in the world. Others eagerly await their ferry crossing to the Italian Boot, or sit sipping Slavic beers in the joints lining Sutomore, soaking in the Adriatic sun.</p>', 1, 0, 134, '+42.5', '+19.64', 'bar', 0, 1),
