(7218, 2403, 'Punakha', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Ensconced neatly in the valley bottoms of the high Bhutanese Himalaya, the nation&rsquo;s one-time capital is a homely, earthy reminder of the country&rsquo;s deep spirituality and wild, rugged backcountry. In fact, nowhere in the highlands of Bhutan does such a visceral picture of local life emerge, in a place where majestic temples rub shoulders with gushing mountain rivers, and sweeping vistas of terraced rice paddy stop only for the occasional mud hut or timber cabin.<br />\n	Don&rsquo;t leave without seeking out the eye-wateringly beautiful Punakha Dzong; the old fortress that defined this hill town as the home of Bhutan&rsquo;s ancient kings. It&rsquo;s laden with priceless artifacts of the bygone age, and, as any Punakha tourist guide will tell you, represents one of the most amazing pieces of castle architecture in the whole country. Nearby, the curious fertility temple of Chimi Lhakhang and the Sangchhen Dorji Nunnery offer further glimpses of the religiosity of the region.<br />\n	Punakha&rsquo;s position high on the mountain plateaus, enveloped by the Jigme Dorji National Park, also makes it the perfect spot for adventure types, with hikers looking to break into the passes of the Himalayas and rafting opportunities aplenty on the Mo Chhu River, while foodies will love the range of chilli-infused staples cooked up by the locals.</p>\n', 1, 0, 31, '27.62', '89.87', 'punakha', 0, 1),
(7219, 2404, 'Phobjikha', '', '', 1, 0, 31, '27.5', '90.17', 'phobjikha', 0, 1),
(7220, 2405, 'Bumthnag', '', '<p class="fr-tag" style="text-align: justify;">In the misty climbs of the Chokhor Valley, white-washed dzongs and ancient temples cling to the verdant hillsides. In Ura, sleepy homesteads rub shoulders with mysterious Buddhist shrines. Close by, the ridges of the Tang valley flourish with apple orchards and buckwheat fields, while the people of Chhume weave traditional woollen yethras amidst healthy meals of puta noodles and kule pancakes. Welcome to Bumthang; the wild, earthy and untrodden spiritual heart of the Bhutanese nation. </p><p class="fr-tag" style="text-align: justify;">To travel through this bucolic section of the Himalaya is to take a journey back in time. Here Bumthang tour guides graciously showcase revered palaces (like the 17<sup>th</sup> century Jakar Dzong), mythical monasteries, (like the Jambay Lhakhang), aged temples, (like the Thangbi Goemba of the 1400s), along with traditional villages and rustic Bhutanese weaving mills. The legendary beauty of the region’s backcountry envelops it all, and travellers can look forward to experiencing the bubbling hot springs at Duer, the serene waters of the so-called Burning Lake, as well as the trekking trails around the greater Himalaya.</p>', 1, 0, 31, '27.75', '90.67', 'bumthnag', 0, 1),
(7221, 2406, 'Trongsa', '', '<p class="fr-tag" style="text-align: justify;">The high-perched town of Trongsa has been the symbolic regal heartland of Bhutan since the kings of the Wangchuck dynasty who reigned here rose as the nation’s monarchs in the early 20<sup>th</sup> century. But Trongsa is also important because of its geography, nestled between the verdant ridges of the Black Mountains and the flowing channels of the Mangde Chhu River, strategically providing a crossroads between the Indian border in the south, the wild national parks in the east and the capital city of Thimphu in the west. </p><p class="fr-tag" style="text-align: justify;">Trongsa tour guides point first-time visitors straight to the mighty Trongsa Dzong complex that looms high in the midst of the rustic town and is arguably the most breath-taking manifestation of traditional Bhutanese defensive architecture going. There is also the Thruepang Palace, the ancestral home of the nation’s royal family and a fantastic museum housed in the Trongsa Tower, one of Bhutan’s best. A walk around town in the meanwhile reveals a curious mix of Tibetan culture and Bhutanese character as seen in its intriguing craft shops and eateries touting carved bowls, handmade textiles and spicy curry dishes to boot.</p>', 1, 0, 31, '27.52', '90.5', 'trongsa', 0, 1),
