(79, 'Ghana', 'GH', '233', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	Often referred to as &ldquo;Africa for beginners&rdquo;, Ghana (&ldquo;Warrior King&rdquo;) also one of its most prosperous nations. Since its first inhabitants of the Bronze Age, it&rsquo;s seen a medley of so many cultures that over 40 distinct languages are spoken throughout Ghana, but English remains the official idiom, a fact first-time foreign travelers to the continent are ever grateful for! It&rsquo;s also blessed with beaches that offer a reprieve from the stifling heat, while historic cities like the capital of Accra boasts eclectic crafts markets as colorful as Ghana itself.<br />\n	Though one of Accra&rsquo;s top attractions is its proximity to the coast, it&rsquo;s also close to the world-renowned botanical gardens of Aburi, where a higher altitude and prominence of lush palm trees manifest in a breezy getaway from the city. And if green is what you&rsquo;re aching for, no travel guide to Ghana would neglect to recommend a trip to Kakum National Park, where you can scale the heights of the rainforest canopy on a network of elevated rope bridges and catch a close-up look at the many birds that call it home along the way.</p>\n', 1, 'ghana', 1, 1),
(80, 'Gibraltar', 'GI', '350', '', 1, 'gibraltar', 0, 1),
(81, 'Greenland', 'GL', '299', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	If there was ever a destination for the most intrepid of worldly travellers, Greenland is it. It&rsquo;s ferocious mountains, unending streams of glacial ice rivers, vast swathes of desolate backcountry, rugged coastal fjords and bubbling pools of volcanic hot springs have been the backdrop for legendary sagas and human exploration for millennia, making this a land at once mysterious and enticing in its inaccessibility.<br />\n	Nearer to the south, nestled in the fjords of the western coast, the quaint and comely capital of Nuuk Town sets the pace. Home to only 15,000 people, this conglomeration of pretty, painted cabins is shrouded by the formidable Sermitsiaq peak, an ever-present reminder of the country&rsquo;s wild and coarse character.<br />\n	For those who want to make the most of their visit, the Qaqortoq region of Greenland remains one of the best places in the world to spot the Northern Lights, while the hot springs of volcanic Disko Island and the smattering of ancient Nordic settlements in the south are oft-recommended by many a Greenland tourist guide.&nbsp;</p>\n', 1, 'greenland', 0, 1),
(82, 'Gambia', 'GM', '220', '<p style="text-align: justify;">\n	A thin strip of oddly carved land enveloped by Senegal, and Africa&rsquo;s smallest country, the Gambia is surprisingly one of east Africa&rsquo;s best-loved beach destinations. With only 50 miles of coastline the spots can get a little busy, but in terms of raw beauty they&rsquo;re difficult to rival. What&rsquo;s more, they receive the full brunt of the Atlantic swell, making them home to some of the most legendary surf breaks on the whole African coast.<br />\n	Out at sea, the tiny Juffureh and James Island offers visitors a glimpse of Gambia&rsquo;s darker history, it&rsquo;s ruined fort complex a relic of the times it was used to facilitate the transportation of slaves and gold across the Atlantic to the New World.<br />\n	Culture-hungry travellers should be sure to ask their Gambia tourist guide for tips on the marketplaces of the capital at Banjul, where bartering locals tout their goods loudly all day long. Away from the city, the Gambia also offers a range of more quintessentially African pursuits, from trekking in the forest at Bijilo to wildlife spotting in the sprawling Abuko Reserve, while upriver in Jangjangbureh hundreds of bird species call out in this veritable bird watchers paradise.</p>\n', 1, 'gambia', 0, 1),
